    "fy-psych-t9-10": "<p><strong>Jean Piaget's theory of cognitive development</strong> proposes that children actively construct their understanding of the world through interaction with their environment, progressing through four universal, qualitatively distinct stages.</p>\n<p><strong>Stages</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Sensorimotor stage (birth-2 years)</strong>: Understanding develops through sensory experience and motor action; key achievement is <strong>object permanence</strong> \u2014 understanding that objects continue to exist even when out of sight (typically develops by ~8-12 months).</li>\n<li><strong>Preoperational stage (2-7 years)</strong>: Development of symbolic/language thought, but reasoning is intuitive rather than logical; characterized by <strong>egocentrism</strong> (difficulty taking another's perspective), <strong>centration</strong> (focusing on one aspect of a situation), and lack of <strong>conservation</strong> (failure to understand that quantity remains constant despite changes in appearance, e.g., the classic beaker-pouring task).</li>\n<li><strong>Concrete operational stage (7-11 years)</strong>: Logical reasoning develops for concrete, tangible situations; conservation, reversibility, and classification abilities emerge, but abstract/hypothetical reasoning remains limited.</li>\n<li><strong>Formal operational stage (11 years onward)</strong>: Capacity for abstract, hypothetical, and systematic scientific reasoning develops.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Key mechanisms</strong>: Development proceeds via <strong>assimilation</strong> (fitting new information into existing schemas) and <strong>accommodation</strong> (modifying schemas to fit new information), driven by the process of seeking cognitive equilibrium.</p>\n<p><strong>Clinical relevance</strong>: Provides a developmental framework for assessing cognitive maturity relevant to competency evaluations, understanding age-appropriate psychoeducation and therapeutic technique selection, and identifying developmental delay when milestones are not reached on the expected timeline.</p>",
    "fy-psych-t9-2": "<p><strong>Erik Erikson's theory of psychosocial development</strong> proposes eight sequential stages spanning the entire lifespan, each characterized by a specific psychosocial \"crisis\" or conflict that must be navigated; successful resolution builds a specific psychological virtue/strength, while unsuccessful resolution leaves lasting vulnerability.</p>\n<p><strong>The eight stages</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Trust vs. Mistrust (infancy, 0-1 yr)</strong>: Successful resolution (consistent, responsive caregiving) builds basic trust and hope; failure produces mistrust, insecurity, and later difficulty forming secure attachments.</li>\n<li><strong>Autonomy vs. Shame/Doubt (early childhood, 1-3 yrs)</strong>: Successful resolution builds independence and will; failure produces shame, self-doubt, and later difficulty with self-assertion.</li>\n<li><strong>Initiative vs. Guilt (preschool, 3-6 yrs)</strong>: Successful resolution builds purpose and initiative-taking; failure produces excessive guilt and inhibition.</li>\n<li><strong>Industry vs. Inferiority (school age, 6-12 yrs)</strong>: Successful resolution (mastery of skills, positive peer/academic comparison) builds competence; failure produces feelings of inferiority and low self-esteem.</li>\n<li><strong>Identity vs. Role Confusion (adolescence, 12-18 yrs)</strong>: Successful resolution produces a coherent sense of identity and fidelity to values; failure produces identity confusion, contributing to adolescent behavioral difficulties and vulnerability to unstable identity in adulthood (relevant to borderline personality pathology).</li>\n<li><strong>Intimacy vs. Isolation (young adulthood)</strong>: Successful resolution builds capacity for genuine intimate relationships; failure produces social isolation and difficulty with closeness.</li>\n<li><strong>Generativity vs. Stagnation (middle adulthood)</strong>: Successful resolution builds a sense of contribution/legacy (through parenting, mentorship, productive work); failure produces stagnation and self-absorption.</li>\n<li><strong>Integrity vs. Despair (late adulthood)</strong>: Successful resolution (reflecting on life with acceptance) builds wisdom; failure produces despair, regret, and fear of death.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Manifestation of unresolved conflicts in adulthood</strong>: Unresolved earlier-stage conflicts are proposed to underlie characteristic adult difficulties \u2014 e.g., unresolved trust issues manifesting as difficulty with intimate relationships, unresolved identity confusion contributing to unstable self-image and relationships (a feature relevant to personality disorder formulation).</p>\n<p><strong>Clinical relevance</strong>: Provides a lifespan framework for psychodynamic case formulation, understanding age/stage-specific presenting difficulties, and guiding developmentally-informed therapeutic intervention.</p>",
